[Patient] How much fluid should I drink daily to manage my heart failure?
[Healthcare Educator] Aim for around 2 liters or 8 cups of fluid per day. 
[Patient] Can I drink any type of fluid, like soda or juice?
[Healthcare Educator] Water is the best choice. Limit soda and juice due to sugar and sodium content. 
[Patient] How do I know if I'm drinking too much fluid?
[Healthcare Educator] Check for swelling in your legs, shortness of breath, or sudden weight gain. 
[Patient] What if I feel thirsty all the time?
[Healthcare Educator] Sip water throughout the day. Avoid drinking large amounts at once. 
[Patient] Can I drink alcohol with heart failure?
[Healthcare Educator] Limit alcohol intake as it can worsen heart failure symptoms. 
[Patient] How can I keep track of my fluid intake?
[Healthcare Educator] Use a water bottle to measure how much you drink each day. 
[Patient] Are there any foods I should avoid for fluid intake?
[Healthcare Educator] Limit high-sodium foods like processed snacks, canned soups, and fast food. 
[Patient] Can I have coffee or tea?
[Healthcare Educator] Limit caffeine intake, as it can affect fluid balance. 
[Patient] Should I be worried if I feel thirsty all the time?
[Healthcare Educator] It's important to drink when you're thirsty, but try to spread out your intake. 
[Patient] How can I deal with fluid intake when I'm out in my unsafe neighborhood?
[Healthcare Educator] Carry a water bottle with you and try to find safe places to refill it. 
[Patient] What if I forget to drink enough water?
[Healthcare Educator] Set reminders on your phone or use a water tracking app to stay on track. 
[Patient] Will managing my fluid intake really help my heart failure?
[Healthcare Educator] Yes, proper fluid management can help prevent complications and improve your overall health. 
